message:
type: DEFER
files: src/click/core.py
spec: Implement batch_size support on the Option class (class Option(Parameter) in core.py):

1) Option.__init__ signature: add a new keyword-only-by-position param 'batch_size: int | None = None' (place it near 'multiple'/'count' params, e.g. right after 'count: bool = False,'). Store as 'self.batch_size = batch_size' (set this before/near self.count assignment, after super().__init__ call).

2) Validation (place near the existing __debug__ validation block that checks 'count' vs 'multiple', around where 'if self.count: if self.multiple: raise TypeError(...)' lives):
   - If batch_size is not None and batch_size < 0: raise ValueError("'batch_size' must be a positive integer.") -- this check must NOT be gated behind 'if __debug__:' (it should always run, unlike the TypeError structural checks).
   - If batch_size is not None and not self.multiple: raise TypeError("'batch_size' is only valid with 'multiple'.") -- this one CAN live inside the existing 'if __debug__:' block alongside the count/multiple check for consistency.

3) Option.to_info_dict: add 'batch_size=self.batch_size' to the info_dict.update(...) call (unconditionally -- include the key even when self.batch_size is None, so to_info_dict always reports it).

4) Option.type_cast_value (the multiple-value branch): currently it does:
   if self.multiple:
       return tuple(convert(x) for x in check_iter(value))
   Change this branch to chunk into batches when batch_size is truthy (i.e. a positive int; guard with 'self.batch_size' truthiness, NOT 'is not None', so batch_size=0 falls through to normal unchunked behavior and avoids a step-0 range error):
   if self.multiple:
       converted = tuple(convert(x) for x in check_iter(value))
       if self.batch_size:
           return tuple(
               converted[i : i + self.batch_size]
               for i in range(0, len(converted), self.batch_size)
           )
       return converted
   (i.e. when batch_size is set, the option's value becomes a tuple of tuples -- each inner tuple has up to batch_size converted items -- instead of one flat tuple. value_is_missing/required checks downstream still work since an empty tuple () is still falsy/equal to () when no values were provided.)

No other files needed for this feature (I don't touch types.py). Thanks for taking ownership of core.py -- ping me (DONE) once merged in so I can review to_info_dict/type_cast_value output matches.
